The article discusses the significance of Earth Day and the importance of taking action on climate change. It highlights the origins of Earth Day in 1970 and the role of Senator Gaylord Nelson in its creation. The article emphasizes the lasting impact of Earth Day and the continued need for environmental protection. It also acknowledges the activism of young people demanding action on climate change. The article mentions the recent climate-related disasters that have affected millions of Americans and emphasizes the disproportionate impact on marginalized communities. It discusses the Biden administration's commitment to addressing climate change and implementing a clean energy plan. The article concludes with President Biden proclaiming April 22, 2021, as Earth Day and urging all Americans to engage in activities promoting environmental protection and a sustainable future.